DIGEST
SB 456 Original 2026 Regular Session Talbot
Present law provides specific provisions requiring judges and court officers who take office
on or after July 1, 1983, to become members of the Louisiana State Employees' Retirement
System (LASERS) by granting the ability to obtain and transfer credits within the system.
Judges and court officers who held office prior to July 1, 1983, continue to be governed by
the retirement laws applicable at the time of their initial service.
Present law further specifies that these specific provisions are inapplicable to those whose
first eligibility for membership in any state retirement system occurred on or after January
1, 2011. While these individuals remain members of LASERS, they are subject to the
standard provisions applicable to regular system members.
Proposed law provides that present law restrictions regarding membership occurring on or
after January 1, 2011, do not apply to retired judges serving on assignments.
Proposed law provides for the definition of "membership in one of the state systems" and
authorizes an irrevocable election to be made within 30 days of employment.
Present law allows a retired judge to be assigned to a court of record while continuing to
receive his retirement pay, although that amount is deducted from his salary as an assigned
judge. Proposed law authorizes the supreme court to determine the applicable compensation
provisions to apply to a retired judge assigned under statute or the court's inherent
